Longitudinal changes in fibrosis markers are associated with risk of cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma in non-alcoholic fatty liver disease.
 Longitudinal changes in non-invasive tests for liver fibrosis such as FIB-4 was strongly associated with progression to cirrhosis and HCC. Impact and implications Risk stratification tools for developing HCC in patients with NAFLD are lacking. Fibrosis-4 (FIB-4) scoring, is a widely available non-invasive test for liver fibrosis, a primary determinant for developing cirrhosis and HCC. In a large retrospective cohort of NAFLD patients, we found that serial changes in FIB-4 over time was strongly associated with progression to cirrhosis and HCC. Integrating serial measurements of non-invasive tests for fibrosis in the care pathway for patients with NAFLD can help tailor HCC risk prevention.
